  <span id="freeText16656026715520986831" style="display:none">“Dreams, after all, are insubstantial things, like mist itself.” <br />― Stephen King, The Mist<br /><br /><br />I read The Mist quite awhile ago and also saw the film. Both of them scared the heck out of me and I cannot say this book is one I enjoyed.<br /><br />I see alot of love for this book on GR and I can see why. Of all the books by King I have read, this one is up there as one of the most genuinely frightening. (And bizarre). <br /><br />But the books by King that I have loved the most are eerie without being as in your face as The Mist is. Now I am not a huge King fan so I do not know all of his books but among my faves are Carrie, Thinner, Needful Things and The Shining.<br /><br />The Mist takes a truly horrifying situation and does put you right there in that claustrophobic supermarket but it is a pretty scary place to be throughout the book. And after awhile the whole thing started getting on my nerves. I guess that is why I am not a fan of Misery either. The setting doesn't change and the scary situations that the characters find themselves in are a constant throughout the book but unlike with some of the books I mentioned that I do like, it is just this one setting for the most part and even though it is suspenseful it wasn't a good suspense for me.<br /><br /> Surprisingly the movie wasn't bungled as most of his books to movies are. (Note: Movie version of Thinner was awful).<br /><br />So for horror purists I do not doubt this was a great read. I like my scares a little more subtle and this was to much for me. 2.5 stars.</span>
